however, art can certainly be created by a human USING artificial intelligence. In this case, the role of AI is, roughly, a tool, like a photoshop.
right now, the AI models only human's brain (0,000... 01% of it), so it can create no art by this definition

Agreed on both points. You put it in a bit simplified way -- endocrine system is definitely no the only factor -- but yes. I do think art must have personality" in it. And human's brain alone is not personality. The whole body form personality."

Space exploration is also a way of exploring a large new horizon of options, but we do not call space exploration art". I mean, art is art and not every "cool stuff" can and should be called art... unless, we want to change the very definition of what art is..."

If your definition of art requires an organism with an endocrine system to make it, then there is no argument and no discussion. But when you start to say “true art” you are going down a well trod path. https:// en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/No_true_S cotsman …
If you view creativity as exploring a large space of options and giving rise to something surprising, then AI is certainly already there. e.g. @hardmaru framed optimization as creativity.

Nowadays, the hype around AI is all about humanizing it, seing some magical powers. Wrong. AI is great at pattern recongnition and it is a useful tool, but it has zero imagination, zero compassion, zero emotion. If you say otherwise, means you never hard-coded any ML.

True art is about emotional message delivered by an artist through his/her technical ability (drawing, etc), and emotions are all based not on the neural networks in our brains, but on the interplay of hormones and other biochemistry in our (human) bodies. AI has none of those.
